  "prompt": "What is the difference between \"don't we verb\" and \" do we not verb\"?",
  "response": "The phrases \"don't we verb\" and \"do we not verb\" are both ways to form negative questions in English, but they differ slightly in their formality and usage.\n\n1. **\"Don't we verb\"**:\n   - This is a contraction of \"do not we verb\".\n   - It's more informal and commonly used in everyday conversation.\n   - Example: \"Don't we have a meeting today?\" This is a casual way of asking if there is a meeting scheduled.\n\n2. **\"Do we not verb\"**:\n   - This is the full form and is more formal.\n   - It is less commonly used in everyday conversation and might be found more in written or formal spoken English.\n   - Example: \"Do we not have a meeting today?\" This sounds more formal and might be used in situations requiring a more formal tone.\n\nWhile both forms are grammatically correct, the choice between them often depends on the level of formality and the context in which you are speaking or writing.",
